ğŸ”¹ What is grep?

grep = Global Regular Expression Print

It is used to search for text/patterns inside files or output.

Think of it like a find tool for text in Linux.

ğŸ”¹ Basic Syntax
grep [pattern] [file]

ğŸ”¹ Examples

1ï¸âƒ£ Find a word in a file

grep "hello" myfile.txt


ğŸ‘‰ Shows all lines from myfile.txt that contain the word hello.

2ï¸âƒ£ Search ignoring case

grep -i "linux" notes.txt


ğŸ‘‰ Finds Linux, LINUX, linux (case-insensitive).

3ï¸âƒ£ Show line numbers with matches

grep -n "error" log.txt


ğŸ‘‰ Prints matching lines with their line numbers.

4ï¸âƒ£ Search in multiple files

grep "main" *.c


ğŸ‘‰ Looks for the word main in all .c files.

5ï¸âƒ£ Search recursively in folders

grep -r "password" /etc/


ğŸ‘‰ Finds "password" in all files inside /etc/ and subfolders.

6ï¸âƒ£ Search using a pipe (filter command output)

ls -l | grep "txt"


ğŸ‘‰ Shows only files with txt in their name from the ls -l output.
